Art by @anetteprs üá∫üá¶ Standing with Ukraine

Caption from Anette:
As we are celebrating Independence Day here today in Estonia, Ukraine is in threat of losing theirs. üíî

We first gained our independence in 1918, however in 1940 Estonia was incorporated into the U.S.S.R. as one of its constituent republics. We remained a Soviet republic until 1991, when, along with the other Baltic states, we declared our independence in 1991. I had a celebratory drawing prepared, but in the light of recent events in Ukraine, this hits too close to home both mentally and physically to ignore. 

Being born in 1997, I was thankfully born into a free country, not one under Russian rule. However the generational trauma is still very prevalent in me and majority of Estonians. It truly hurts to think that Ukraine is under threat of losing their independence, as we are celebrating ours.

Its important to note here that this isn't to stir hate towards Russians. They are also victims of this tyranny. Many of my Russian followers have expressed anger, sadness and confusion of what is going on, and deep disappointment in the actions of their leaders. So please, do not harbor hate towards the Russian people. Criticizing a government is not criticizing a nation. Hoping that they will find the courage and stand against this tyranny and force to bring about change. In the words of Edmund Burke: "All that tyranny needs to gain a foothold is for people of good conscience to remain silent."

So, here I have drawn two women, one in Estonia's national clothes and the other in Ukrainian national clothes. Standing together in hopes that Ukrainian independence will remain as strong as its roots. 

We see you, and hurt for you. Happy birthday Estonia, and praying for you, Ukraine. üá∫üá¶ üíôüñ§ü§ç

Caption from Anette:
As we are celebrating Independence Day here today in Estonia, Ukraine is in threat of losing theirs. üíî

We first gained our independence in 1918, however in 1940 Estonia was incorporated into the U.S.S.R. as one of its constituent republics. We remained a Soviet republic until 1991, when, along with the other Baltic states, we declared our independence in 1991. I had a celebratory drawing prepared, but in the light of recent events in Ukraine, this hits too close to home both mentally and physically to ignore. 

Being born in 1997, I was thankfully born into a free country, not one under Russian rule. However the generational trauma is still very prevalent in me and majority of Estonians. It truly hurts to think that Ukraine is under threat of losing their independence, as we are celebrating ours.

Its important to note here that this isn't to stir hate towards Russians. They are also victims of this tyranny. Many of my Russian followers have expressed anger, sadness and confusion of what is going on, and deep disappointment in the actions of their leaders. So please, do not harbor hate towards the Russian people. Criticizing a government is not criticizing a nation. Hoping that they will find the courage and stand against this tyranny and force to bring about change. In the words of Edmund Burke: "All that tyranny needs to gain a foothold is for people of good conscience to remain silent."

So, here I have drawn two women, one in Estonia's national clothes and the other in Ukrainian national clothes. Standing together in hopes that Ukrainian independence will remain as strong as its roots. 

We see you, and hurt for you. Happy birthday Estonia, and praying for you, Ukraine. üá∫üá¶ üíôüñ§ü§ç

I‚Äôm finding it hard to concentrate as war sit so close to my doorstep. Focusing more time on things I can control, like building out the Troopy, while things are unsettled out in the chaos of the world. Especially learning that Russian forces are now in control of Chernobyl.

I have no fear of Russia invading Georgia (again) anytime soon. (So, yes, I am safe.) But watching what‚Äôs happening to Ukraine is having a heavy effect on me and the city I call home. If you haven‚Äôt seen the videos of 30,000 people coming out to stand by Ukraine, it gives me chills.

While most of you sit in your home without fear of being forced from it, of ever being separated from your loved ones, of ever knowing what it sounds like to hear a bomb hit nearby, of ever being put in a position to stand by your neighbors with guns in hand to defend the place you call home, that‚Äôs the reality of what‚Äôs going on.

These are people. And they are fighting harder than anyone in the world right now for their lives and the lives of their families.

So, instead of going to get that latte from Starbucks today, or that sushi dinner, how about you help instead.

Donate to World Central Kitchen @wckitchen who is providing meals at the border in Poland where 150,000+ people have fled. They will begin serving hot meals in Moldova and Ukraine soon.

Donate Bitcoin or other digital currency (or cold hard cash) to the Ukrainian Army through @comebackalive2022 at savelife.in.ua/en/donate/

Ukrainewar.carrd.co is another great resource on where ‚Äì and how ‚Äì to support the efforts on the ground. Find additional ways to support Ukraine‚Äôs Armed Forces, purchase medical supplies, help children affected by the war, and donate to protect free on-the-ground journalism by supporting the Kyiv Independent, all here.

If you‚Äôre in Tbilisi, you can donate to the Ukrainian Embassy, who will be delivering supplies. Go to helpukraine.center to learn more.

Finally, continue to stay aware of what‚Äôs happening by following sources close to the ground, including @withukraine and @ukraine.ua, and by reading the Kyiv Independent.

Oh, and dump out that terrible Russian vodka you‚Äôve been drinking while you‚Äôre at it.

Ukraine and Me

As I was watching the news last night, I thought to myself, "What impact does the Ukraine and Russia war have on my life? I don't know anyone who lives there...oh my God I do know someone." It dawned on me that my dear art mentor lives in Kyiv, Ukraine. Andrew who just last week helped me with my Google Doodle art submission and has submitted college recommendation letters for me lives in the center of the battlefield!

I contacted him right away via Skype and he sent me a video of a Russian missile hitting the apartment building near his apartment. Earlier today he gave me an update saying that Putin just bombed a holocaust memorial complex. He can see what's left of that building from the 12th floor of his apartment. As of the time of his update, 5 civilians have been killed, and are 5 injured. I can't believe this is happening and I know someone who is stuck in the middle. He asked me to spread the word that Russia is killing civilians.

It is truly terrifying and heartbreaking that just days ago Andrew, like many others, was living his life just as normal as the rest of us, and now fighting for his livelihood! What's cynical is the fact that Russian citizens aren't being told the truth of Ukraine's situation through their media outlets. My pal who lives in Siberia (which is within Russia's mainland) likely found out about what's happening through the internet!

If you're willing, please consider donating to Ukraine's cause in protecting their nation and helping people to leave the country. If you're feeling stuck on where to send your money, a resource Andrew recommended is savelife.in.ua/en/donate (the link will be in my linktree bio). This is a third-party charity organization that sends funds to the Ukrainian military and others in need at this time.

Another place you can direct your funding in getting Jewish immigrants to leave Ukraine is the Feed Israel Foundation (feedisrael.org). Other resources will be linked in my bio as well for helping natives, refugees, and immigrants to escape. 

If you don't want to give your funds to this cause PLEASE be praying for Andrew, his family, the internationals who are trying to escape!

@nazarfuryk ‚Ä¢ Stand with Ukraine

‚ÄúThese are my archival photos from 2015 to 2018. During the last few days I kept going back in my archive and my memory to those years - when there was an occupation of Crimea by the Russian Federation; when the war in the Eastern part of Ukraine, which was not acknowledged in time, started and continued until February 24, until now the full-scale invasion...

In 2014, when Ukrainians did succeed in being at a high point of freedom, feeling united as Ukrainians and as a nation, to bring down the pro-Russian government. Right after that Revolution of Dignity in Ukraine, putin and his council approved their military intervention to our country to "normalize the political situation". For me it's important to analyze and to reflect on how it was and how things have changed now.

In my experience it was very surreal (in a bad way) to go from peaceful Kyiv in 2015 to the East as a photographer, and see the exact opposite of peace and a safe life. I had to quickly adapt to that terrible war routine in the East, because otherwise you had no chance to stay alive.
February 24, the first days of the full-scale invasion of Russia into the territory of my country I could not film, could not eat and could not sleep. My fear was very real. It was like a balloon - bigger than my body and the bodies of my closest people all together.

What Russia is doing now - this is fascism and genocide. They attack maternity wards and bomb shelters with civilians, buses with civilians and homes. I want it all to end as soon as possible, but end in a way that in 5-10-30 years history does not repeat itself. I want the evil empire [russia] to fall, and all who carry out these atrocities and committing genocide should be fully punished.‚Äù

We are People of Ukraine and we stand for Ukraine against russian invasion.

We are musicians, so the best thing we could do is to let the world know about the terror of russia through our music. What russian army does to our people, to our children and women, how they destroy our homes and our lives. Rape, violence, genocide, murder, marauding - this is what they bring. This is a war between humanity and barbarism, love and hate, kindness and pure evil.

We know that for the rest of the world this is somebody else's war. We do our best to stop this horde so you can sleep in peace unafraid of air strikes, so you can think of summer vacation and not about how to survive another day..

Speak up about war, say it loud, insist on help for Ukraine. Silence may kill more than a missile.
